---
import WizardLayout from '../../layouts/WizardLayout.astro';
import TerminalMockup from '../../components/TerminalMockup.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<WizardLayout
  title="Verify the Output"
  currentStep={6}
  totalSteps={6}
  prevHref={`${base}craftsman/exercise`}
  nextHref={null}
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Check the work</h1>
  <p class="text-slate-400 mb-8">
    You've seen Claude Code analyze real code. Now evaluate what you got.
  </p>

  <div class="space-y-8">
    <!-- Evaluation criteria -->
    <div class="p-5 rounded-xl bg-slate-800/50 border border-slate-700">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">How to judge the output</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-300">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="text-amber-400 shrink-0 mt-0.5">&#9670;</span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Did it find the real bugs?</strong>
            Not style nits or theoretical issues &mdash; the actual logic errors
            that would cause failures in production.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="text-amber-400 shrink-0 mt-0.5">&#9670;</span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Were the explanations accurate?</strong>
            Check the reasoning. A correct fix with wrong reasoning is a red flag.
            A tool you can't audit is a tool you can't trust.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="text-amber-400 shrink-0 mt-0.5">&#9670;</span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Were the proposed fixes sound?</strong>
            Would you accept this diff in a code review? Would you need to rewrite
            it, or is it close to what you'd write yourself?</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="text-amber-400 shrink-0 mt-0.5">&#9670;</span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Did it miss anything?</strong>
            No tool is perfect. Note what it caught and what it didn't. That
            calibration is the whole point of this exercise.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- What to try next -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">If that was useful, try these next</h2>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-slate-800/30 border border-slate-700">
          <p class="text-white text-sm font-medium mb-1">Explain unfamiliar code</p>
          <TerminalMockup>
            <p class="text-slate-300 text-xs">
              <span class="text-emerald-400 select-none">$ </span>claude 'explain the request lifecycle in src/server/ — trace a request from entry to response'
            </p>
          </TerminalMockup>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-slate-800/30 border border-slate-700">
          <p class="text-white text-sm font-medium mb-1">Review a diff critically</p>
          <TerminalMockup>
            <p class="text-slate-300 text-xs">
              <span class="text-emerald-400 select-none">$ </span>git diff HEAD~1 | claude 'review this diff — focus on correctness, not style'
            </p>
          </TerminalMockup>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-slate-800/30 border border-slate-700">
          <p class="text-white text-sm font-medium mb-1">Refactor with constraints</p>
          <TerminalMockup>
            <p class="text-slate-300 text-xs">
              <span class="text-emerald-400 select-none">$ </span>claude 'refactor src/auth.ts — extract the token validation into a pure function, keep the same public API'
            </p>
          </TerminalMockup>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Closing -->
    <div class="p-6 rounded-xl bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-500/10 to-orange-500/10 border border-amber-500/20">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">Form your own opinion</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm">
        You've seen what Claude Code does, how it does it, and where it falls
        short. The rest is up to you. Use it where it earns its place in your
        workflow. Ignore it where it doesn't. That's the right approach.
      </p>
      <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm mt-3">
        For reference:
        <code class="px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-slate-800 rounded text-slate-300">/help</code> lists
        available commands,
        <code class="px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-slate-800 rounded text-slate-300">CLAUDE.md</code>
        gives Claude Code context about your project, and
        <code class="px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-slate-800 rounded text-slate-300">Esc</code> cancels
        any operation mid-flight.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</WizardLayout>
